[[File:RobertsonFieldHouseDemo1.jpg|thumb|right|Demolition of the Field House, April 2008]] '''Robertson Memorial Field House''' was a multi-purpose [[arena]] on the [[Bradley University]] campus in [[Peoria, Illinois]]. The arena, built inside two surplus [[World War II]] [[airplane hangar]]s in 1949 for $400,000 (${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|400000|1949|r=-5}}}} in present terms), had a 3-foot (1 meter) raised floor as its sports court and event stage.<ref name="bub-rmfh">{{cite web | title = Robertson Memorial Field House | url = http://www.bubraves.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=3400&KEY=&ATCLID=130292&SPID=1497&SPSID=19327 | date = 2005-06-22 | accessdate = 2008-02-24 | publisher = [[Bradley University]] }}</ref>
The Field House was dedicated on December 17, 1949, and named in honor of [[Alfred J. Robertson]], usually known as "Robbie" or "A.J.", who served as Bradley's coach and athletic director for 28 years.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www2.pjstar.com/index.php?/fieldhouse/archives/robertson_reunion1/ | title = Robertson Reunion | first = Kirk | last = Wessler | work = [[Peoria Journal Star]] | date = 2008-02-22 | accessdate = 2008-11-08 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080229081722/http://www2.pjstar.com/index.php?%2Ffieldhouse%2Farchives%2Frobertson_reunion1%2F | archivedate = 2008-02-29 | df = }}</ref> When it opened, it had a [[seating capacity]] of 8,300, but more aisles and wider seats soon reduced capacity to 7,800.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www2.pjstar.com/index.php?/fieldhouse/archives/origins_of_a_mecca/ | title = Origins of a Mecca | first = Ryan | last = Ori | work = [[Peoria Journal Star]] | location = [[Peoria, Illinois]] | date = 2008-03-28 | accessdate = 2008-11-10 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110715090824/http://www2.pjstar.com/index.php?%2Ffieldhouse%2Farchives%2Forigins_of_a_mecca%2F | archivedate = 2011-07-15 | df = }} Part of the "Remembering Robertson" section.</ref> Since a 2004 renovation, its capacity had been 5,000.<ref name="bub-rmfh" />
From 1949 to 1982, it was home to the [[Bradley University]] men's [[basketball]] team, whose winning record there was 400&ndash;100 before they moved to [[Carver Arena]] in 1982.<ref name="bub-rmfh" /> From 1982 until 2008, the women's basketball and [[volleyball]] teams played their home games at the arena. It hosted the [[Missouri Valley Conference]] men's basketball tournament title game in 1980.{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}} The 2007&ndash;2008 season was the final year of use for Robertson Memorial Field House; it hosted [[NCAA]] women's basketball and volleyball.<ref name="mcm-080309">{{cite news | url = http://www2.pjstar.com/index.php?/fieldhouse/archives/robertson_takes_one_final_shot/ | date = 2008-03-09 | title = Robertson takes one final shot | first = Ed | last = McMenamin | accessdate = 2008-11-10 | location = [[Peoria, Illinois]] | work = [[Peoria Journal Star]] | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110715090832/http://www2.pjstar.com/index.php?%2Ffieldhouse%2Farchives%2Frobertson_takes_one_final_shot%2F | archivedate = 2011-07-15 | df = }}</ref>
In April 2008, Robertson Memorial Field House was demolished.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www2.pjstar.com/index.php?/fieldhouse/archives/the_field_house_is_coming_down/ | title = The Field House is coming down: How will they do it? | work = [[Peoria Journal Star]] | location = [[Peoria, Illinois]] | date = 2008-04-15 | accessdate = 2008-11-10 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110715090837/http://www2.pjstar.com/index.php?%2Ffieldhouse%2Farchives%2Fthe_field_house_is_coming_down%2F | archivedate = 2011-07-15 | df = }}</ref> Bradley's new women's basketball arena, the [[Renaissance Coliseum]], opened in October 2011 on the same plot previously occupied by the Field House.
