The '''Shrine Bowl''' was a postseason [[college football]] bowl game. The first game was played on December 18, 1948, at [[War Memorial Stadium (Arkansas)|War Memorial Stadium]] in [[Little Rock, Arkansas]] between [[Hardin–Simmons University]] and [[Ouachita Baptist University|Ouachita Baptist College]].<ref>Foldesy, Jody. "Bowls burgeon as big business", ''The Washington Times''. December 21, 1997. Page A1.</ref> The 1949 edition was held in Carbondale, Illinois as the [[Indiana State Sycamores football|Indiana State]] Sycamores faced the Salukies of [[Southern Illinois University]].
==Game result==
{| class="wikitable" ! Date !! colspan="2" | Winner !! colspan="2" | Loser !! Location |- | December 18, 1948 || '''[[Hardin–Simmons Cowboys|Hardin–Simmons]]''' || '''41''' || [[Ouachita Baptist University#Athletics|Ouachita Baptist]] || 12 || [[Little Rock, Arkansas]] |- | November 26, 1949 || '''[[Southern Illinois Salukis football|Southern Illinois]]''' || '''41''' || [[Indiana State Sycamores football|Indiana State]] || 14 || [[Carbondale, Illinois]] |} A series of games sponsored by the Shriners as a charity event in Honolulu in December 1941 and referred to by some as the Shrine Bowl was interrupted by the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor. Teams from Willamette University and San Jose State travelled to Hawaii to play against each other and the University of Hawaii. The Willamette team lost to the Hawaiians in the opening game on Saturday, December 6, but other games were cancelled due to the onset of the war. The teams were among the first civilians evacuated in a convoy to San Francisco a couple of weeks later.
==See also== * [[List of college bowl games]]
