{{Infobox stadium | name = The Oval | nickname = | image = | caption = | fullname = | location = [[Wednesbury]], [[England]] | coordinates = {{Coord|52.5626|-2.0007|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | surface = Grass | cost = | architect = | capacity = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | acreage = | tenants = [[Wednesbury Old Athletic F.C.|Wednesbury Old Athletic]] }}
'''The Oval''' was a [[cricket]] and [[association football|football]] ground in [[Wednesbury]], [[England]]. It was the home ground of [[Wednesbury Old Athletic F.C.|Wednesbury Old Athletic]], and also hosted two [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] matches at the start of the [[1893–94 Football League|1893–94 season]].
==History== The ground was located to the north-west of Wednesbury town centre, and featured a pavilion located close to St Paul's road, which ran along the northern boundary. At the end of the [[1892–93 Football League|1892–93 season]] Walsall left [[the Chuckery]] to move to [[West Bromwich Road]]. However, the new ground was not ready at the start of the 1893–94 season, so the club played two matches at the Oval. The first on 2 September 1893 saw Walsall lose 3–1 to [[Birmingham City F.C.|Small Heath]], whilst the second match was played on 9 September, with Walsall losing 5–0 to [[Port Vale F.C.|Burslem Port Vale]].<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888–2005'', Yore Publications, p35, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref> Despite it being a temporary home, the 5,000 spectators present at the Small Heath game was higher than the club's highest League attendances at either the Chuckery or West Bromwich Road.<ref>Smith & Smith, p35</ref><ref>Smith & Smith, p144</ref>
The ground is now an open sports field, with Walsall's modern [[Bescot Stadium]] located a few hundred metres away on the other side of the [[M6 motorway]].
